article.headline: Saint Louis 51, Missouri State 50
article.story: ST. LOUIS (AP) -- Ian Vouyoukas scored on a tip-in at the buzzer, giving Saint Louis a 51-50 come-from-behind victory over Missouri State on Monday night. Deven Mitchell scored 15 points for Missouri State, which squandered an 11-point second-half lead. The Bears (9-2) made only one basket in the final 9:28 and missed three shots and the front end of two bonus free throw situations in a scoreless final three minutes. Saint Louis (9-2) got three shots on its final possession after Nathan Bilyeu missed from inside for Missouri State with about 9 seconds left. Kevin Lisch missed from about 15 feet and Tommie Liddell threw up an air ball on the rebound from the baseline, but the 6-10 Vouyoukas was there to hoist it into the basket. One official signaled that the score came too late, but after a video review at courtside determined that the ball went in with one-tenth of a second to go. After watching the play six times, referee Gerry Pollard said, "It's good, boys!" Lisch had 15 points and Vouyoukas had 13 points, seven rebounds and four blocks for Saint Louis, which has won four in a row. The Billikens ended Missouri State's five-game winning streak, and beat the Bears for only the second time in the last eight meetings, despite committing a season-worst 22 turnovers. Bilyeu added 11 points and six rebounds for Missouri State, which had won five in a row and just missed cracking the Top 25 this week. Leading scorer Blake Ahearn, who averages 17 points, was scoreless and missed all four of his shots. Missouri State was in control much of the second half and led 46-35 with about 9:30 to go before Saint Louis, energized by reserve Luke Meyer, rallied down the stretch. Meyer had two points, three rebounds and an assist in a 12-2 run that shaved the deficit to 48-47 with 3:39 to go. Bilyeu made a pair of free throws with 3:18 left for Missouri State's final points. Meyer hit a layup with 43 seconds to go to set up Vouyoukas' game-winner. Liddell, Saint Louis' second-leading scorer with a 14.3-point average, was responsible for nine of the turnovers to offset a six-point, nine-rebound effort. Vouyoukas had six turnovers. Ahearn was held out of double figures for only the second time all season.
